0":"1180","Gowerton, Glamorgan, Wales":"Gowerton, Glamorgan, Wales","Bramber Castle, Sussex, England":"Bramber Castle, Sussex, England","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales"},"nl":{"January 1180–":"januari 1180–Overleden","1190–1275":"1190–1275","1205–Female":"1205–Overleden","1180–Female":"1180–Overleden","1217":"1217","1190":"1190","1205":"1205","1275":"1275","January 1180":"januari 1180","1180":"1180","Gowerton, Glamorgan, Wales":"Gowerton, Glamorgan, Wales","Bramber Castle, Sussex, England":"Bramber Castle, Sussex, England","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales"},"en":{"January 1180–":"January 1180–Deceased","1190–1275":"1190–1275","1205–Female":"1205–Deceased","1180–Female":"1180–Deceased","1217":"1217","1190":"1190","1205":"1205","1275":"1275","January 1180":"January 1180","1180":"1180","Gowerton, Glamorgan, Wales":"Gowerton, Glamorgan, Wales","Bramber Castle, Sussex, England":"Bramber Castle, Sussex, England","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lindsay","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Lindsey in Lincolnshire, England. This is first found in the form <i>Lindissi</i>, apparently a derivative of the British name of   Lincoln  . To this was later added the Old English element <i>ēg</i> ‘island’, since the place was virtually cut off by the surrounding fenland. The surname was taken to Scotland at an early date and is the name of an important and powerful Scottish family.","Irish: adopted as an equivalent ofvarious Gaelic names (see   Lindsey  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Linzy","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish, Irish, or English   Lindsay   or   Lindsey  . Compare   Lenzy  ."]},{"name":"Linzey","meanings":["English: variant of   Lindsay   or   Lindsey  ."]},{"name":"Lindsey","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Lindsay  .","Irish: shortened and Anglicized form of various Gaelic surnames, as for example <b>Ó Loingsigh</b> (see   Lynch   1), <b>Mac Giolla Fhionntóg</b> (see   McClintock  ), and <b>Ó Fhloinn</b> (see   Flynn   and   Lynn  )."]},{"name":"Lincoln","meanings":["English: habitational name from the city of Lincoln, so named from an original British name <i>Lindo-</i> ‘lake’ + Latin <i>colonia</i> ‘settlement, colony’. The place was an important administrative center during the Roman occupation of Britain and in the Middle Ages it was a center for the manufacture of cloth, including the famous ‘Lincoln green’.","African American: adoption of the surname in 1 above, in honor of Abraham Lincoln, the 16th president of the US, who abolished slavery.","History: Abraham Lincoln (1809–65), 16th president of the US, was the son of an illiterate laborer, descended from Samuel Lincoln, who had emigrated from England to MA in 1637."]},{"name":"Linsey","meanings":["Scottish, Irish, or English: variant of   Lindsay   or   Lindsey  .","Americanized form of German   Linse   or Swiss German <b>Linsi</b>, see   Lins  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Amabilia De Lindsay was born in January 1180, in Gowerton, Glamorgan, Wales. She married John De Burgh in 1217, in Bramber Castle, Sussex, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"January 1180–":"jaanuar 1180–Surnud","1190–1275":"1190–12